post_text: With the new executive order and guidance provided by the MHSAA yesterday, VCS plans to move forward with fall sports. The state of Michigan and the MHSAA have prioritized the health of students and communities throughout the pandemic. Yesterday‚Äôs executive order and MHSAA update are clear signs that health experts have decided it is safe to resume sports. As with all the other executive orders related to sports, it takes a few days for the dust to settle and for questions to get answered. At this time, we are working to get more clarification on a variety of topics, including spectator limitations, mask requirements, and contest schedules. We plan to offer further, more detailed guidance next week.

These are high-resolution images which will arrive to you in a .Zip file. While it is possible to access these through a cell phone, a computer is recommended. post_text: It is with great sadness that we announce that Bootcamp has been canceled for this year. We want to thank Mrs. G for all of the work she puts into this program and it has been a great experience and tool for our incoming Kindergartners. However, given the state of the Covid-19 virus and the plans for schools, we felt this was the safest option for our students and staff. We look forward to continuing this program in the fall of 2021!

Dear V.C.S. Parents,

In an effort to gain insight and understanding of parent‚Äôs perspectives regarding the return to school this fall, we are asking that everyone please take a few minutes to complete the following survey, Vestaburg Return to Learn Survey. The survey takes less than 5 minutes to complete and the information is essential and will help guide the planning committee. Please feel free to reach out to us if you need assistance with completing the survey. Thank you for your time and please know that the V.C.S. staff and administration are working hard to put together plans for safe and effective learning for all students.

Please note that the software used is a product of Michigan State University and thus, the survey will have the university logo. We are asking that everyone complete the survey by Tuesday, July 21, 2021.

post_text:
Borrowed from a friend and fellow educatorü•∞:

Today is a big day for educators in Michigan... today we will get the Return to School plan from our Governor.

We know there is going to be some information that incites wonder and maybe challenges our current thinking/opinions about what school should look like...

All I ask of my friends:
Extend grace... at all levels... more than you think is deserved or necessary... we are all receiving this information at the same time. While we have had many pre-planning conversations, the hardest work starts today. This is the first of many stepping stones we'll climb before the start of school at the end of the summer.

Love you all... Keep it positive my friends ‚ù§Ô∏è

Today, I am not going to post a senior spotlight, I will pick that up again tomorrow.

Instead, I want to promote the radio event that begins at noon today. Our school is included in this event. The event has been posted on this page, earlier this week. However, here is the link again (https://www.facebook.com/events/2253965431578125/). It also provides information on how to listen online.

There has been a lot of work being done on a constant basis and some of it "behind the scenes" to honor these seniors, and this is one of the ways.

Our Valedictorian(s) and Salutatorian collaborated together to create a speech to submit to the radio and put it into a video format for us to post online for all to see (the video has been posted to this Facebook page). The task that was given to these students was no easy feat. Please, today, watch this video, listen to the radio, seniors... put on your cap and gowns, listen for your name, take pictures, etc! Congratulations class of 2020 enjoy the radio event today.

ELEM FUNDRAISER UPDATE!
After a LONG debate and negotiating, the fundraiser is complete. The company is not able to take paper orders at this time. If you have paper orders, please void these and inform the person ordering. If you placed online orders these are being shipped to you, the person ordering, OR the school. If they are shipped to the school they will be delivered to the student's family.

Thank you for your patience regarding this matter. This is not the outcome I hoped for, however, the circumstances were not in our favor. Also, thank you to those who previously placed online orders.

post_text: How do you thank to those that are held in highest of esteem in an organization? If any of you have been a part of our school system or have had to work with the school system you have witnessed first hand the backbone of our organization. They are our first line of communication and they represent what is best about our school. In case you have not figured it out, I am talking about Karen Grover, Valorie Palmer, Amanda Micallef, Ashley Arntz, Christina Hartman, and Tracey Reed. These ladies are appreciated more than I express in this post, however, I wanted to say thank you for all of your hard work and dedication. You are the face of our great school and your efforts do not go unnoticed. Personally, I cannot thank you all enough for what you do. You are the first to volunteer to go above and beyond your daily duties and your heart for our students and our school is second to none! So, I hope everyone will join me in saying thank you to these great people. Thank you and hopefully we will be able to celebrate in person soon! WE ARE VESTABURG because of you ladies!

post_text: Parents of College-Bound Seniors: If your financial situation has negatively changed during the COVID-19 pandemic please know that colleges and universities are working on financial aid relief. You will need to contact the financial aid office of your students' selected college or university. They will use your 2020-2021 FAFSA information along with current household financial information to make a determination on Fall tuition assistance. Please note, if you have not filed your 2020-2021 FAFSA, you can still do so at: www.FAFSA.gov

REQUESTS ARE DUE BY TOMORROW (Thursday, April 17th by 8:00 am)

Pickup will be on Monday, April 20th from 1:00 pm - 3:00 pm.

VCS Students and Parents,

Chromebooks will be provided to any student in grades Kindergarten - 11th, by request only. If a 12th grade needs to finish earning required credit for a class they are not currently passing, they must contact Mrs. Leja (jwarner-leja@vcs-k12.net) directly.
Chromebooks may be used for access to enrichment learning opportunities during this extended closure time.
Primary learning will be given in the form of paper packets.

Chromebooks are NOT needed for these primary learning opportunities.

Chromebooks will be available for drop off (with food deliveries) and parent pick up on Monday, April 20th from 1:00 - 3:00 PM.
Chromebooks must be returned to the school on the first day of the 20-21 school year.

post_text: The title and honor of Valedictorian and Salutatorian are given to the student(s) that has the highest and second-highest grade point average (GPA) among their class. Please join me in congratulating these seniors for their hard work, and this well-deserving honor.

As we heard from Governor Whitmer, we will be closing Vestaburg Community School's building effective Friday, March 13th at 3:00 pm through April 5. Our facilities will be completely closed to all activities which include all athletic events. This includes practices, open gyms, fitness center use, or any team gatherings (team banquets, spring training trips, and team bonding activities). This also includes all youth sports and community meetings and/or events.

We are also in the process of evaluating activities and events throughout the month of April. Please know that we will be providing updates regarding specific events as we get more clarity and final decisions are made. Thank you for your patience as we continue to adapt to the everchanging circumstances.

shared_text:
HEALTHCARE.UTAH.EDU
When Sick Kids Should Stay Home
text:
Dear Parents and Guardians;
As you know, our number one priority is always the health and safety of our students and staff. With that being said, we are in the midst of cold and flu season and are seeing increased numbers of students going home ill. Thus, we are asking that if your child is exhibiting any of the following symptoms including, increased and constant coughing, vomiting, especially more than once, fever, and/or diarrhea that you keep your child home to help reduce the exposure of other students and staff. Furthermore, if your child is experiencing any of these symptoms we would encourage you to take them to a physician. In addition, please continue to keep stressing the importance of hand-washing to your child. Your help and diligence in helping us keep our students and staff healthy are greatly appreciated.
Please visit this website for additional information: https://healthcare.utah.edu/healthfeed/postings/2016/01/stay_home_sick.php.

HEALTHCARE.UTAH.EDU
When Sick Kids Should Stay Home

Good Afternoon!

Just a quick reminder: The WATCH D.O.G.S Special Kick-Off Meeting will be held TONIGHT, Tuesday January 7th at 7:00pm in the Commons Area at VCS!

The VMS Strong Parent Group will be launching a Nation Wide Program called WATCH D.O.G.S. This progam is a family and community engagement educational initative that has been actively involved in public schools all across Amercia since 1998. The WATCH D.O.G.S. program is being implemented at the Middle School level here at VCS. The WATCH D.O.G.S. initiative has a goal to make a difference in the lives of Middle School students and build a positive Middle School culture as well. We are seeking MALE VOLUNTEERS that are willing to make a difference, be a role model, and build positive relationships with students.

post_text: High School Career Center Parents and Students: Today (12/2), the Career Center experienced a technology glitch that resulted in an email being sent to us indicating that there was no PM session due to a power outage. Therefore, we did not send our students. When we found out that this email was sent in error, and that they did have power and were in session, it was too late to rectify the situation on our end. First, we have communicated with the career center and they have assured us that all students will be marked as a school-related excused absence; therefore, there will be no penalty for their lack of attendance. Second, we have requested the process to be changed moving forward so we can be sure that accurate communication is in place. If you have any further questions regarding this, please feel free to contact the high school office. Thank you!

FAFSA NIGHT AT VHS

Vestaburg High School will be hosting a Financial Aid Information night on October 23rd at 6 pm in the HS media center. We will have a financial aid representative from Montcalm Community College here to provide information, answer questions and help with filling out the FAFSA applications.
What you need to bring to fill out the FAFSA:
FSA ID number- can be set at: studentaid.ed.gov under the FAFSA: Apply for Aid tab. This will be necessary to submit the application and it could take a few days to finalize, so please have this ahead of the meeting date.
2018 tax information ‚Äì FAFSA uses prior-prior year info.
For further information on FAFSA please use the web address above.
